What do you mean by Arrays?

Definition:
An array is a collection of elements of the same data type stored at consecutive memory locations.
Arrays help to store multiple values using a single variable name.

Example and Declaration:

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    int numbers[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};  // Declaration and initialization of array
    for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        printf("%d ", numbers[i]);
    }
    return 0;
}


 Explanation:

int numbers[5]; → Declares an integer array of size 5.

Elements are accessed using an index like numbers[0], numbers[1], etc.

2️⃣ What do you mean by Functions?

Definition:
A function is a block of code that performs a specific task and can be reused multiple times in a program.

Types of Functions:

Library Functions → Already defined in C libraries (e.g., printf(), scanf()).

User-defined Functions → Created by the programmer.

Example (User-defined function):
#include <stdio.h>

// Function without return value
void greet() {
    printf("Hello, welcome to C programming!\n");
}

// Function with return value
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    greet();  // Calling function
    int sum = add(5, 10);
    printf("Sum = %d", sum);
    return 0;
}

3️⃣ What do you mean by Pointers?

Definition:
A pointer is a variable that stores the memory address of another variable.

Example (Initialize and use pointer):
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int *p;       // Declaration of pointer
    p = &a;       // Initialization (stores address of a)

    printf("Value of a: %d\n", a);
    printf("Address of a: %p\n", &a);
    printf("Value through pointer: %d\n", *p);
    return 0;
}


 Explanation:

*p is used to access the value stored at the address.

4️⃣ What are the types of Arrays?

Types:

One-Dimensional Array (1D)

Two-Dimensional Array (2D)

Example of 1D Array:
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    int marks[5] = {80, 70, 90, 85, 95};
    for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        printf("Marks[%d] = %d\n", i, marks[i]);
    }
    return 0;
}

Example of 2D Array:
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    int matrix[2][3] = { {1,2,3}, {4,5,6} };
    for(int i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
        for(int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
            printf("%d ", matrix[i][j]);
        }
        printf("\n");
    }
    return 0;
}

5️⃣ Explain the Types of Operators in C

Operators:
Operators are special symbols used to perform operations on variables and values.

Types with Examples:
Type	Example	Explanation
Arithmetic Operators	+ - * / %	Perform mathematical operations
Relational Operators	== != > < >= <=	Compare two values
Logical Operators	`&&	
Assignment Operators	= += -= *= /=	Assign or update values
Increment/Decrement	++ --	Increase or decrease by 1
Example Code:
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    int a = 10, b = 5;

    // Arithmetic
    printf("Addition: %d\n", a + b);
    
    // Relational
    printf("Is a greater than b? %d\n", a > b);
    
    // Logical
    printf("Logical AND: %d\n", (a > b) && (b > 0));
    
    // Assignment
    a += 2;   // a = a + 2
    printf("After assignment: %d\n", a);
    
    // Increment / Decrement
    a++; b--;
    printf("Increment a: %d, Decrement b: %d\n", a, b);

    return 0;
}
